WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:11.840
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to start talking about the basics of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:18.320
algebra. We're going to start off with very simple&nbsp;
algebra, the kind that students learn in public&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:24.640
school. This kind of algebra involves&nbsp;
unknown quantities which are denoted by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:30.960
letters, usually the letters at the end of&nbsp;
the alphabet like x, y, and z. So for us now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:37.600
x is an unknown number, and we're given an&nbsp;
equation like this one: x plus two equals seven.

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:41.840
It's a game. If you have a ten-year-old&nbsp;
daughter like I do, you can ask her,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:47.280
"With x plus two equals 7, what is x?" She'll&nbsp;
think for a little while and figure out that x&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:53.520
equals 5. If I give her a slightly harder one like&nbsp;
this, it might be a little bit more challenging:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.520 --> 00:01:01.600
x plus 13 equals 41. But eventually, she might&nbsp;
figure out that x equals 28. However, with a more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:07.280
complicated question like this involving&nbsp;
bigger numbers: x plus 378 equals 642,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.280
how is she going to figure out that the&nbsp;
answer is 264? Some kind of manipulation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:20.320
of the equation is necessary to reduce it to&nbsp;
a simpler equation. It turns out that although&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:25.840
the original equation involves addition, the&nbsp;
actual solution of the problem uses subtraction.

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:34.080
So if we start off with x plus 378 equals 642, the&nbsp;
way we solve that is by rewriting that equation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:42.000
in this form: we bring the 378 on this side to the&nbsp;
other side, where the plus sign turns into a minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.840
sign. So that's how we can then calculate that&nbsp;
x equals 264. These two equations are considered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.400
to be equivalent in the sense that if we have a&nbsp;
solution to this one, then it's also a solution&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:58.960
to this one. Conversely, if we have a solution to&nbsp;
this one, then it's also a solution to this one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:07.440
This is a basic strategy in algebra, even in more&nbsp;
complicated algebra, to take an equation involving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:14.640
some unknowns and simplify it to get an equivalent&nbsp;
equation which is easier or simpler to solve.

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:23.920
Here are some other examples: y minus 5 equals 3,&nbsp;
illustrating that the variable doesn't have to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:31.120
x. It could be y or z or anything else. In this&nbsp;
case, there's a minus 5 on the same side as the y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:36.880
and so we like to bring the minus 5 to the other&nbsp;
side where it becomes a plus five. So we get y&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:44.080
equals three plus five, which of course is eight.&nbsp;
How about this equation: z plus ten equals two?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.840
Well, if we bring the ten to the other side with&nbsp;
the minus sign, we get z equals two minus ten.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:57.120
Now the answer is minus eight, and we see that&nbsp;
even if we start with a problem involving only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:04.160
natural numbers, the solution might very&nbsp;
well take us into the realm of the integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:12.240
So in general, for this kind of equation, we&nbsp;
need to consider our numbers to include integers.

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:18.320
Now let's have a look at some slightly more&nbsp;
sophisticated problems. Suppose we have the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:25.040
equation 3x equals twelve, and our convention&nbsp;
is—and we have to be clear about what the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:33.440
convention is—that 3x means three times x. You can&nbsp;
see why we might use this convention because if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:39.920
we're using x as a variable, then it can easily&nbsp;
get confused with our multiplication symbol.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:48.800
So when we write 3x, it means 3 times x, or&nbsp;
similarly, 3y means 3 times y, and so on.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:56.080
Alright, well if 3 times x equals 12, then if&nbsp;
you know your multiplication table, x equals 4&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.080 --> 00:04:02.080
because 3 times 4 is 12. If 7x equals 49, then&nbsp;
from your multiplication table, x equals 7.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:09.840
But if you have 19x equals 893, your&nbsp;
multiplication table probably doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:15.440
go up that far, so you don't just automatically&nbsp;
know what the answer is. Although the question&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:21.520
involves multiplication, the solution uses&nbsp;
division. In other words, we take this equation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:31.280
19x equals 893 and replace it with the equivalent&nbsp;
equation obtained by dividing both sides by 19. If&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:36.720
we divide this by 19, we just get simply x, and if&nbsp;
we divide this by 19, well we get that fraction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.760
and 893 divided by 19 turns out to&nbsp;
be 47 once you do the long division.

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.480
Here are some other examples in the&nbsp;
same kind of spirit: 4y equals 36.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:57.600
Well, then y equals 36 over 4, and that's&nbsp;
9. Here's another example: 5z equals 11.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:06.240
Dividing by 5, we get z equals 11 over 5.&nbsp;
But now, as opposed to the previous cases,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:13.200
11 divided by 5 is not a natural number&nbsp;
or an integer, so we must remain with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:21.840
this quantity as simply a fraction. This kind&nbsp;
of question generally requires us to extend&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:29.360
our number system to include rational numbers.&nbsp;
Fractions or rational numbers—I recall that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:34.960
fractions for me are always positive and rational&nbsp;
numbers can include negative fractions as well.

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:40.000
So we can use both of those types&nbsp;
of equations and put them together&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:48.800
to get somewhat more complicated examples. For&nbsp;
example, 3x plus 4 equals 11 minus 2x plus 8.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:56.240
That's a single equation in an unknown variable&nbsp;
x. The assumption is that this variable x and this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:01.440
variable x represent the same mystery number, and&nbsp;
we have to find out what that mystery number is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:10.080
What we generally do is replace this equation&nbsp;
with a series of equivalent equations obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.680
from this one by standard operations. Generally&nbsp;
speaking, we try to get all the x's on one side&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:19.280
and all the numbers on the other side. Then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:23.200
try to simplify everything until we&nbsp;
finally have x equals some number.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:31.600
So in this case, 3x plus 2x on this side becomes&nbsp;
a plus 2x when we bring it over there. We have 11&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:38.240
plus 8. The 4 here becomes a minus 4 when we&nbsp;
bring it to the other side. So 5x equals 15,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.240 --> 00:06:46.640
and x equals 3. Another example involving some&nbsp;
fractions involving our unknown variable x:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:57.200
6x minus 1 divided by 2 equals 5 plus 3x divided&nbsp;
by 7, and x becomes the fraction 17 over 36.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:05.680
Manipulation of these kinds of algebraic equations&nbsp;
relies heavily on a prior understanding of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:11.680
arithmetic with fractions. If you don't&nbsp;
know how to do arithmetic with fractions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:18.960
fluidly, then you're always going to struggle&nbsp;
with algebra. This is a very important point.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:24.480
It's one reason why—get rid of those&nbsp;
calculators when you're teaching students&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:31.360
mathematics. Force them to work with pen&nbsp;
and paper to become confident and skilled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:36.960
at arithmetic with fractions because&nbsp;
it's the basis for moving to algebra.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:42.560
So here's a fun little party game that you're&nbsp;
all probably familiar with. Let's look at a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:47.840
particular example. Suppose that we're asked to&nbsp;
pick a number and say add three. We're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:53.040
think of our number as being x instead of 7&nbsp;
or 12 or whatever. Let's think of it being an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:58.880
x; this turns out to clarify what's going on. So&nbsp;
after we've added three, we have x plus three.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:06.160
Suppose the next instruction is to multiply it by&nbsp;
two. Well, two times x plus three is 2x plus six.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:09.840
The next instruction is to add ten. Alright,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.840 --> 00:08:15.440
so then we have 2x plus 16. The next&nbsp;
instruction might be to subtract 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:24.000
Well, then we have 2x plus 12. Then we are told to&nbsp;
divide by 2. Well, if we divide 2x plus 12 by 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:31.920
what we're going to get is x, because 2x divided&nbsp;
by 2 is x, plus 6, because 12 divided by 2 is 6.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:37.200
Okay, and then finally we're asked&nbsp;
to subtract our original number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.160 --> 00:08:42.560
So there's the number we got right now;&nbsp;
the original number was x. If we take x&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:47.440
plus six and we subtract x, then we end&nbsp;
up with six. And you can see that yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:51.680
the answer is six. It is independent&nbsp;
of the number x that you started with.

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:56.640
Next time, we're going to have a&nbsp;
look at solving quadratic equations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:02.240
which is a big step up from these linear equations&nbsp;
we've been looking at so far, but it's still part&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:07.840
of Baby Algebra. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

